Workers in the clothing manufacturing industry have become the first employees in South Africa to receive an industry-wide COVID-19 Unemployment Insurance Fund relief payout. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Workers in the clothing manufacturing industry have been thrown a lifeline. They have become the first employees in South Africa to receive an industry-wide COVID-19 Unemployment Insurance Fund relief payout. This follows a collective agreement at the bargaining council, which will see the workers being paid their full wages. READ: What you need to know about UIF benefit The money is transferred to a dedicated bank account for the sector. The Southern African Clothing and Textile Workers Union says all 63,000 employees in the industry will be paid. The union says it’s also meeting regularly to look at ways it can help workers even further. READ: Call for more funds to save SMMEs “The engagement on whether the money will be enough or will sustain the workers in the event there’s an extension of the lockdown, that discussion is still carrying on in the industry,” said Sactwu Deputy General Secretary Vilina Membinkosi. Factories may now be empty but workers at least don't have to worry about where their next meal is coming from. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.